', 'When I lived in DC, every year there was a day I referred to as Tom Petty Day. It was a different day every year, and you never knew when it would be, but you know when it arrived — a warm, sunny spring day when you first felt that the weather had turned a corner from sometimes warm/sometimes cold to consistently warm. In the sun and the warmth I’d realize Tom Petty Day was upon us, open the windows, hit play on Petty’s greatest hits CD and make things official with the first few notes of American Girl. I loved Tom Petty Day.
.
I was sad when I realized there is no Tom Petty Day in San Francisco; the weather just isn’t consistent or predictable enough; you never feel like the sun and warmth will stay for a more than a few days, certainly not for months. And so now I celebrate the occasional Tom Petty One Desperate Moment, when the weather is spectacular and the fog lifts, outside and in.
.
*well she was an American girl, raised on promises ....*
.
(Why Tom Petty? ‘Cause I nearly wore that CD out spring semester freshman year of college, and as a result associate it strongly with a bright, warm DC spring day. Nothing more to it than that. Well, that and the fact that Tom Petty was awesome.)

', 'APS is Arizona’s largest utility. It has a monopoly over the electricity business in much of the state. A monopoly over something everyone *has* to buy is a pretty good thing to have, if you’re into making money. And APS is *very* into making money. Half a *billion* dollars in profit last year alone.
...
But APS is never satisfied; not with hundreds of millions in profits. CEO Don Brandt personally took home millions. All for selling something people could only buy from them — and that they *had* to buy.
... It gets hot in the summer in Arizona. Like, 115 degrees hot, daily, for long stretches. In weather like that, you need air conditioning, you need fans — you need electricity. Or you die. ...
APS didn’t *need* the fifty bucks or so that 72-year-old Stephanie Pullman was a few days late in paying when APS decided to cut off her electricity on a 107 degree day. But APS sure *wanted* it.
...
A week later the county sheriff’s office found Stephanie in her home, dead of environmental heat exposure, her body already decomposing.
...
This will become more common, if we let it. Climate change will make hot days like that more common. An economy rigged to allow wealthy corporations to do whatever they want in the name of making a buck will lead to more millionaires like Don Brandt, too busy counting their cash to give a damn who dies when their electricity gets shut off. ...
If we let it.

', "Happy five-year anniversary to one of the most special shows I’ve ever been to. …

', 'Nein filters - full Stop. A leafy day ended with some fun after blowing the leaves out of the gutters and some tag team raking. The view from above was only surpassed by the views on the ground!!!
', '"Patience is a virtue David"
-
That's what my sister said to me once when I was a kid… as she trapped me inside of a flattened fridge box by sitting on it in the middle of the lawn.
-
I literally conquered claustrophobia in that moment.
- 
Today I said nothing. Just watched.
-
Patience is a virtue little one.
-
#WinterClaustrophobiaIsReal
', 'As bizarre as this will sound to my fellow Albertans, I’m actually kind of sad to see winter finally go… ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Partly because I snowboarded a few times at the end of the season and that was really fun…
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But mainly because I’m fairly obsessed with these colour gradients at dusk. There is something magical about the northern winter sunsets framed with the blackened silhouettes of spruce trees!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I was at a youth activity several weeks ago and had to literally run outside and snap the sky!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#yeg  #sunset #colours #gradient #sky

', 'In honor of my Grandpa Steed’s 90th Birthday we celebrated at home with dessert before dinner, root beer floats (sadly using un-authentic Kickapoo JoyJuice: his homemade clear-your-sinuses-out root beer), and reading some stories from his personal history book.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ The girls love their Great Grandpa Steed! Bruce David Steed is one of my main hero’s and I count it as an honor to bear his name. He is always happy, willing to serve, funny, and a great example to those around him!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
He is a follower of Christ, husband, math teacher, father of 8, fixer-upper, grandfather, painter, really good under-ducker (I know from childhood experience on the old acreage swing), hard worker, stealer of his own grandkids’ ice cream, calf deliverer (and brander), lifelong learner, maker of magical childhoods, great-grandfather, wood bird carver, creative thinker, and servant to all… to name a few minor attributes😉
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Now, back to Bruce’s Kickapoo JoyJuice… I remember tearing up every time I drank it as a kid; it was sooo carbonated & yeasty😖 Somehow tough, I always sought it out at the next family reunion, and eventually I cultivated a taste for it!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I aspire to be like my grandpa in so many ways ⬆️see list above⬆️. So, I was thrilled when Lyndsey suggested I should make labels to cover the A&W root beer bottles. I still need to learn the recipe from the old silver fox himself, but for today it was fun to pay tribute to him by having some Kickapoo JoyJuice of our own!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
∾⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
T

', 'All real, all today, all #nofilter @pacificsands #staypacificsands #pacificsandscontest
', '3 years later… still hanging around the #SavilleSportsCentre This time it’s her turn to play though!
', 'I am grateful for Lyndsey (@lyndseyolsen). She is incredibly smart, very accomplished, a consummate professional, a pursuer of excellence… and naturally radiant! Basically everything she sets her mind to turns out amazingly, and… she also has an incredible intuition for beautiful days and adventures that shouldn’t be missed! It’s hard to imagine what life would have been like if she ended up going to UVic instead of UofA! #GiveThanks
', 'Yesterday felt glorious! It was hovering just above freezing, but with the brilliant sun it felt really quite balmy! 

I had just spent a goodly amount time standing in a huge line at Costco to get groceries and had come up short on TP (though the cart was otherwise quite full)… as I exited the building the feeling of the sun on my face hinted at what was coming.

As I pushed the cart through the slushy parking lot I was overwhelmed by a positive feeling! I felt grateful to have health, family, food to eat, and a planet that really is amenable to human life when compared to other options!

I was also grateful for all the snow and colder weather that preceded that moment which had the effect of sweetening that sunny-day-feeling!

#GiveThanks
', 'I love the sky… sunsets, clouds, rain, snow, sun dogs, rainbows… all of it! The colours, texture, and grandeur of it all (from up high, or down low) is sure to leave me elevated in spirit!
#GiveThanks
', 'Grateful for an adventure-mobile that fits our family perfectly, amazing places in our own province to visit, summer-vibes, a big ol’ tent, cousins,  #Waterton, and that magical-black-box-à-la-Mary-Poppins-bag to carry extra stuff!
#GiveThanks
']

', 'Opening match at Audi Field last night surpassed all my expectations. Definitely some kinks to work out but overall it was worth the 7+ year wait.

', 'My favorite coffee experience in Seattle was at @lamarzoccocafe where this great reminder was displayed. Piero’s family has been making espresso machines for almost 100 years. 
They have a great space that they share with a radio station so after I finished drooling over the $5-10K home espresso machines we sipped on a cup from their featured roaster of the month while listening live.

They happened to be featuring @coffeecollectif while we were there which brought back memories of our visit to Copenhagen in 2015!

#coffee #inspiration #specialtycoffee #seattle #seattlecoffee #latergram

', 'I resisted for a long time but finally picked up a road bike. 

Once the COVID shutdown started I’ve been doing longer rides to make up for my lost bike commutes. I also began riding more on roads due to the trails being overcrowded. That led to looking for something that was more comfortable on lengthier outings and easier on the climbs up the hills of Arlington. 

By the time I landed on a bike I wanted there were only two left in the country in my size due to everybody buying bikes this summer. I contacted a shop in Ohio that was willing to ship the bike to my local bike store and even cover the shipping and assembly costs!

Still going to keep the trusty hybrid around for riding with the kids and commuting once I go back in to the office (next year? 🤞🏻).

', 'Meet our wine director, Andy Miller, from Venice, CA

“I was touring playing music for a living in the past and would always look for new local craft beer to try. From that it quickly turned into finding new wines. Natural wine wasn’t a thing I was aware of at the time until a few of my older friends caught onto this little bar in Los Feliz - Bar Covell. It was the first time I had wine with varietals I was familiar with done in a totally different style. The wines were fresh and bright, acid driven and slightly funky. 

A few restaurants and cocktail bars later, I began working at a natural wine bar where my mind was blown by everything we carried. Grower producer champagne, old skin-contact wine from Georgia, hybrid grapes from the northeast and everything beyond. 

I’d love to pour you something special and chat natty wine next time you’re in!”

", "The D&D gaming table is done. This was made for my buddy Mike, and the idea was to have a biiiiiig table that would fit 6 players and a DM  comfortably, but still fold away for storage when not in use. It features individual slide-in trays for each player's personal stuff, and plenty of space on the main tabletop for maps, etc. The legs fold up into the main body, the trays store underneath the tabletop, and the two halves collapse and latch together for storage.

The main body was made of Birch and Birch plywood, while the legs are made of solid Red Oak. Everything is stained dark walnut, with about 4 coats of semi-gloss lacquer finish, to provide protection and some spill-proofing. This is by far the largest thing I've built to date, and I learned a ton while doing it.

', "Today something different from the usual format. That's what I love of London, the mix of old architecture steps away from modern buildings, the City of London is full sights and corners like this one in St Helen's Square. 
The St. Andrew Undershaft church is one of the few rare churches built around the 15th century which has survived both the Great Fire of London in the 17th century and the Blitz bombing during the second World War. The Church has been partially restored after the IRA's bombings in the 90s.

In the background, the skyscraper named The Scalpel and a reflection of the 30 St Mary Axe, commonly known as the Gherkin Tower because apparently Londoners like to nickname buildings by their look and shape 🥒

', 'I’m not sure I should have quit my day job. 
Two weeks ago, I returned home from visiting family in Canada. They’d given me a check for inheritance my aunt had left me

On the ferry ride back to the states I talked with my girlfriend, and we both decided I should put in my two weeks at my day job, the store I’d been at for the last nine years, take a portion of the money and try to draw comics full time. Take six months to dedicate to comics. See what happens. 
I’d been thinking of leaving that job for years, but I‘d been dreaming of doing comics full time all my life. 
When I left for Canada three weeks ago, I had no concrete plans to quit, yet yesterday was my last day at that job.

I’m thrilled, overwhelmed, and frightened about what I’ve done. 
Guess I better go make comics.

', '(Crossposted from matthewbogart.net) Several months ago, novelist, comedian, poet, storyteller, and president of Write Bloody Publishing, @derrickbrownpoetry wrote me with a plan. A friend of his was redesigning a huge building in a small town and wanted to turn it into a collection of shops designed by different creators. He wanted Derrick to dream big and design a bookstore.

Derrick told me his plan for Fascination Station. It was to be a train station, with a checkout counter modeled after Grand Central stations information kiosk. It would have cubby holes for reading, set into in the back wall designed like bunks on a train car. Large displays would be inset in arches showing landscapes rolling by. Travel posters advertising departure times for famous fictional destinations would hang on one wall, and shelves would roll away, so folding chairs could pull out from a secret compartment and an audience could watch authors read from the back of a full size caboose, as if they were on a whistle-stop tour.

It sounded wonderful, and Derrick wanted me to draw it.

While I make detailed 3D models for my comics, I’d never designed something like this. Something that was to become an actual physical place. Something that needed to fit in exact dimensions and be usable by flesh and blood people. It was a heck of a lot of fun, and the illustration came together in no time.

Fascination Station Book Store overhead view
An overhead view of Fascination Station – a Write Bloody Bookstore
Sadly, things fell through. The Fascination Station only exists in these drawings.

But gosh does it make me want to go to a bookstore. So I think I will.
